Well, the first thing I look at is my circle of competence. I’ve spent my life buying simple, predictable businesses—insurance, consumer products, railroads, banks. Google is an advertising‐driven technology company with a sprawling mix of search, cloud, YouTube and AI bets. I don’t fully understand all the moving parts or regulatory risks in that business, so right off the bat I’m out of my comfort zone.  

Second, the moat. Google certainly has brand recognition and network effects from its search engine and user data, but with no detailed data here I can’t gauge durability—monopolies attract regulators and competitors.  

Third, management quality. I’ve seen that Alphabet’s leadership has allocated capital into projects like Waymo and various moonshots. Without stronger proof of disciplined capital allocation and shareholder‐friendly behavior I can’t weigh in.  

Fourth, financial health. There’s no balance-sheet or earnings data provided, so I can’t tell if there’s consistent free cash flow or a fortress balance sheet.  

Fifth, valuation. With no intrinsic value estimate or margin of safety calculated, I have no idea if the stock trades at half its worth or twice its worth.  

Sixth, long-term prospects. Search and digital ads could persist for decades, but technology and regulation move quickly. That uncertainty is not what I look for in a forever holding.  

Finally, compared to opportunities I know—Coca-Cola’s brand, Apple’s ecosystem, BNSF’s network—Google doesn’t fit my recipe. There’s no penalty for passing on an idea I don’t understand. So I’ll pass, staying neutral until something changes.
